<title>Eigenvalues</title>         
 
<para xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.s1">
For each pair of values of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.m1">\nu</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.m2">k</Math> there are four infinite unbounded sets of real eigenvalues <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.m3">h</Math> for which equation (29.2.1) has even or odd solutions with periods <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.m4">2\!K\</Math>!
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.s2">
or <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.m5">4\!K\</Math>!
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.s3">
.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="4" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.s4">
They are denoted by <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.m6">a^{2m}_{\nu}\left(k^{2}\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.m7">a^{2m+1}_{\nu}\left(k^{2}\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.m8">b^{2m+1}_{\nu}\left(k^{2}\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.m9">b^{2m+2}_{\nu}\left(k^{2}\right)</Math> , where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C29.S3.SS1.p1.m10">m=0,1,2,\ldots</Math> ; see Table 29.3.1.
</sentence>

